    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 115, n. <citedRange>110</citedRange>, fig. 66</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.222</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>026600</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>91</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64529"><name nymRef="#Καλλίστρατος">Καλλίστρατος</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65600"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Σίμυλος">Σιμύλου</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Kallistratos fils de Simylos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Kallistratos son of Simylos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Kallistratos figlio di Simylos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>كاليستراتوس بن سيميلوس</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>About the provencance, Oliverio only mentioned 'Necropolis'. Thorn, for all those published by Oliverio in the years 1930 thought that it should be 
                the North Necropolis, on the assumption that only that Necropolis was explored by the Italian teams of the time. Moreover, about the present stele, Thorn 
                noticed that «it recalls two others (here <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr029300</ref> and <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr029350</ref>) in situ above Tomb 
                N.240 and may belong to a cluster of sarcophagi nearby». As we could not trace the two others, we cannot discuss this point.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
